First, we rewrite the left-hand side using the sum-to-product identity: \[ \sin x + \sin 2x = 2 \sin \left( \frac{3x}{2} \right) \cos \left( \frac{x}{2} \right) \] Thus, the equation becomes: \[ a \cdot 2 \sin \left( \frac{3x}{2} \right) \cos \left( \frac{x}{2} \right) = 2 \sin \left( \frac{3x}{2} \right) \cos \left( \frac{3x}{2} \right) \] Dividing both sides by 2: \[ a \sin \left( \frac{3x}{2} \right) \cos \left( \frac{x}{2} \right) = \sin \left( \frac{3x}{2} \right) \cos \left( \frac{3x}{2} \right) \] Factoring out \(\sin \left( \frac{3x}{2} \right)\): \[ \sin \left( \frac{3x}{2} \right) \left[ a \cos \left( \frac{x}{2} \right) - \cos \left( \frac{3x}{2} \right) \right] = 0 \] This equation holds if either: 1. \(\sin \left( \frac{3x}{2} \right) = 0\), which gives \(x = \frac{2\pi}{3}\) in \((0, \pi)\). 2. \(a \cos \left( \frac{x}{2} \right) - \cos \left( \frac{3x}{2} \right) = 0\).
